2 Data cleaning

We have some work to do here. We’ll need to adjust a few classes to factors and dates. We will also change game type to represent iOS or Android.

#Change a few columns to factors % use iOS or Android for column game
run <- 
run %>%
  mutate(
    game = ifelse(game == "3368", "iOS", "Android")
  ) %>%
  mutate_each(funs(as.factor),
            c(app_version,
              game,
              type,
              event)
  )

#Let's confirm the changes

2.1 Missing install dates

There a lot of missing install dates. It looks like because the install date is logged only when certain events are logged. We will use the match funtion to pair user and their install date and then update the original dataset.

#Map install dates
matchrun <-
run %>%
  distinct(user, install.date) %>%
  filter(!is.na(install.date)) %>%
  select(user, install.date)

matchrun

  mutate(
    installed = as.Date(installed, format = "%Y%m%d")
  )

2.2 Unix time

Remember that weird time variable? Looks like it’s unix time so we’ll have to have R convert it to a readable time.

#Convert unix to Los Angeles time
run <- 
run %>% 
  mutate_each(funs(as.POSIXct(run$time/1000, origin="1970-01-01", tz="AMERICA/LOS_ANGELES")), time)

3 Retention

Now our data is ready lets look into retention!

3.1 Preparing data for retention analysis

We need to a format where the dataset will give us the user, their first install date, and their subsequent logins. Day0 represents the count of users.

#Create columns marking if users are 0 or 1 for logging in that day
retentionOG <-
run %>% 
  mutate(
    day0 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 0, 1, 0)),
    day1 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 1, 1, 0)),
    day2 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 2, 1, 0)),
    day3 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 3, 1, 0)),
    day4 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 4, 1, 0)),
    day5 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 5, 1, 0)),
    day6 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 6, 1, 0)),
    day7 = as.integer(ifelse(date - installed == 7, 1, 0))
  ) 

head(retentionOG) %>%
  select(user, installed, day0:day7)

By collapsing the rows we can get a total count of how many users installed the game on a certain day and the sebsequent visits from day 1 to day 7

#Using summarise_each sum collapse the rows based on the installation date of user.
retention <-  
retentionOG %>%
  group_by(installed) %>%
  distinct(user, date) %>%
  summarise_each(funs(sum), contains("day"))

3.3 Plotting for android vs iOS

Is there a difference in retention for platforms? There could possible be a bug on one platform that affects retention. Let’s graph to check like we did above.

#Retention by platform and use additional parameter group_by for game

  retentionOG %>%
  group_by(installed, game) %>%
  distinct(user, date) %>%

4 Tutorial bounce

When users start the game they have to go through the tutorial. A drop off during the tutorial represents issues with the tutorial. Maybe a step is too long, confusing, or should be taken out entirely.

Using the event column let’s take any item that has the word ‘tutorial’

#Extract 
tutorial.bounce <-
run %>%
  filter(grepl("tutorial", event))

Due to the last implementation of tutorial, there are mirror event names that were used previously but thrown away. We will filter these out with the count number as future builds of the games will no longer use this.

#Line
tutorial.bounce.l <-
  tutorial.bounce %>%
  group_by(event) %>%
  mutate(
    count = n()
  ) %>%
  distinct(event) %>%
  filter(count >50)

tutorial.bounce.l

We need to columns that represent how many users started each step, how many finished it, and how many users left.

#Create remaining, and bouncing users
tutorial.bounce.l <- 
tutorial.bounce.l %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  mutate(
    remaining = lead(count), 
    remaining.p = lag(round(remaining / 475, 2)),
    bounce.p = 1 - remaining.p
  ) %>%
  select(event, count, remaining, remaining.p, bounce.p)

tutorial.bounce.l

Due to using lag, there are a couple of NA’s. We can easily replace these with the appropriate 1 and 0.

#Fill in NAs with 100% and 0
tutorial.bounce.l$bounce.p[is.na(tutorial.bounce.l$bounce.p)] <- 0
tutorial.bounce.l$remaining.p[is.na(tutorial.bounce.l$remaining.p)] <- 1

Let’s plot~

#Line plot with remaining percentages as labels 
ggplot(tutorial.bounce.l, aes(x = reorder(event, -count), y = count, label = remaining.p)) +
  geom_point(size = 1.5, color = "light blue") + 
  geom_line(group = 1, color = "light blue ") + 
  theme_few() +
  geom_text(size = 3, hjust = -.3, vjust = -.5) +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)
  ) +
  ggtitle("Tutorial bounce rate") +
  ylab("") +
  xlab("Tutorial step")

There is a 32% drop off from the beginning to the end of the tutorial. There are clear dropoffs between tutorial.start and tutorial.startingline 9%!

5 Conclusion

With more information we can create multiple cohorts to explore user data. Some that come to mind are:

  • PU vs non paying
  • Whales vs one time spenders
  • Balance issues
  • A/B comparisons
  • Improvements to KPI for events, updates, etc
